 Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":105,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Stansfield was born about 1350, in Stansfield, Yorkshire, England, his father, William Stansfield, was 31 and his mother, Joan Burton, was 30. He married Barbara de Lascelles about 1385, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1350–":"umbes 1350–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1352–Female":"1352–Surnud","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1356–Female":"1356–Surnud","1352–1389":"1352–1389","1380–1457":"1380–1457","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","–1406":"–1406","1320–1372":"1320–1372","1322–Female":"1322–Surnud","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","1356":"1356","1322":"1322","1354":"1354","1320":"1320